(26, 1, '2015-02-21 14:00:53', '2015-02-21 14:00:53', 'Tell me if this sounds familiar: A friend of yours finally gets out of a long, hurtful relationship and, after some time, starts dating again. After a few mediocre dates, your friend meets someone who seems like a catch, and when you ask about this new person, your friend describes him or her as “nice, not angry or aggressive at all.” You ask about this person’s positive qualities, but your friend is more relieved at the absence of negatives.\r\n\r\nMaybe you’ve seen this, and maybe it even describes you. I know I’ve heard it often from friends of mine. I’m struck that they are so grateful to find people with what seem to be such minimal qualifications, as if it were enough to lack clear negatives regardless of any positives. (To be fair, “nice” is a quality which is often misunderstood as bland or cloying, and has become undervalued in favor of excitement and physical attractiveness—but that’s a topic for another day.)\r\n\r\nThe more I thought about it, however, the more I realized that this approach to dating—focusing primarily on the significant downsides that you want to avoid—is an important first step to finding someone you want to be with. I’ve written previously about relationship “deal-breakers,” but I focused primarily on superficial qualities such as height and income rather than harmful character traits such as aggression and abusiveness. I’ve also written on the positive things we should focus on instead, primarily finding someone who makes you feel the way you want to feel. Perhaps naively, I thought that should be enough: focus on the positive thing(s) you want and don’t sweat the little things that annoy you but are of little consequence in the big picture. However, that may not be enough, especially for people who have been hurt in previous relationships (which, to some degree, applies to many if not most of us).\r\n\r\nFinding someone that makes you feel the way you want to feel may be more easily said than done. One reason is that we might not know exactly how we want to feel. But we often have a much better idea how we don’t want to feel.\r\n\r\nFor example, no one wants to feel like the target of someone’s anger and aggression. Neither does anyone want to be subject to emotional abuse or insults, or being made to feel unworthy or unwanted. Many of us endure these things, sometimes convincing ourselves we deserve them, but very few go into a relationship seeking them. All of the positive qualities in the world may not mean much if a person makes you feel horrible, and it makes perfect sense to make sure a person doesn’t lead you to feel that way before you consider his or her positive qualities.\r\n\r\nConsider it a defensive version of the Hippocratic Oath applied to dating: First, find someone who seems likely to “do no harm.”\r\n\r\nIt would be a wonderful world if no one ever made their partners feel threatened, neglected, or inadequate. In the real world, however, all too many do this, whether they intend to or not, and we are wise to guard ourselves against them. It’s tragic that we have to shield ourselves against behavior that no one should have to expect. But often it’s a crucial first step to finding a person who’s right for you. Once you make sure you don’t accept someone who makes you feel horrible, you can start finding someone who makes you feel great.\r\n\r\nAs the classic song says, you''ve got to "accentuate the positive [and] eliminate the negative (link is external)"—but not necessarily in that order...', 'Smoking and Weight: Those "Burnt-out Ends of Smoky Days"', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '22-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-02-21 14:00:53', '2015-02-21 14:00:53', '', 22, 'http://localhost/wordpress/22-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
